  userImage = "<img src='https://example.com/malicious.jpg'>";
}
```

In the example, we are displaying the user's name and image, but the image source contains a malicious script. By enabling Strict Contextual Escaping, Angular will automatically escape the HTML markup. However, if it's disabled, you should escape the `userImage` string to prevent XSS attacks.

To escape user input safely, you can use Angular's `html` attribute binding:

```typescript
import {Component} from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <h1>Welcome to my app!{{ htmlData }}</h1>
    <img [src]="safeSrc(htmlData)">
  `
})
